"DIABETES": Disease

The etiology of diabetes mellitus (DM) is multifactorial, with both genetic and environmental factors contributing to its development.

{"ETIOLOGY": Type of study described, "DIABETES MELLITUS": Disease, "GENETIC FACTORS": Factor, "ENVIRONMENTAL FACTORS": Factor}

The pancreas plays a crucial role in the development of diabetes, as it is responsible for producing insulin, a hormone necessary for the uptake and utilization of glucose by the body.

{"PANCREAS": Organ, "INSULIN": Hormone, "GLUCOSE": Molecule}

In type 1 diabetes, the immune system attacks and destroys the insulin-producing beta cells of the pancreas, leading to an absolute deficiency of insulin.

{"TYPE 1 DIABETES": Disease, "IMMUNE SYSTEM": Organ, "BETA CELLS": Cell}

In type 2 diabetes, insulin resistance and beta cell dysfunction contribute to the development of hyperglycemia.

{"TYPE 2 DIABETES": Disease, "INSULIN RESISTANCE": Condition, "BETA CELL DYSFUNCTION": Condition}

